The Katsina State government has said that plans were on ground for the state government in collaboration with federal government and some non governmental organisations (NGOs) to take Almajiri pupils off the streets by formalising the Islamic system of education. Governor Aminu Bello Masari of the state, disclosed this while playing host to an Islamic sect named ‘Maj’mau Durqu Sufiyya’ yesterday. The governor stressed further the need to restructure the almajiri system of education in the state by taking statistics and introducing mathematics and english language lessons. “The essence is to change the narrative in the state that over 900,000 children are out of school. We will make assessments from various schools to know those who are not from the state and those that are indigenes,” he said. Governor Masari urged the sect to support the program , adding that the precarious situation the state has found itself was as a result of illiteracy and drug abuse, hence the need for muslim clerics to rise up the challenge to address them. “As a leader, you have a great role to play with the teachers in your respective schools by drawing their attention on this,’ he said. Earlier, leader of the sect, Shek Abubakar Caranci, thanked the governor for the warm reception, and expressed sect’s  plans to unite their followers and execute key major projects in the areas of education, healthcare service among others.